betterquesting:10.desc:8:
I know I've been super nice and have given you all the water purification supplies you've needed up to this point, but it stops now!

Not the niceness, 'cause we're friends.

It's about time you made your own charcoal filters though.

For this, you'll also need to make some paper from sugar cane.

If you haven't found some already, you should be able to find it growing on the bank of a body of water.

§nTask 1§r: Make paper.
§nTask 2§r: Make a charcoal filter.

The title pretty much says it all.

This is how you upgrade your tool belt.

§nTask 1§r: Make a belt pouch.

You found a waystone and tried to use it without even knowing what you were getting into. This sounds about right, for someone wandering through the Block Rock Desert.

Waystones sometimes appear at villages, and sometimes in other places too. Once you get far enough along you can make them on your own. Travel past a certain distance (or between dimensions) will cost you XP. 

As your reward you can choose between your own waystone (choose where you place it carefully!) or a warpscroll is a single use item which will allow you to go to any waystone you have activated. To use the warp scroll hold down right click until the memu pops up.
waystones are cool if you can find some ender eyes
Did you know that there is a difference between a cone and a delineator? And that delineators are sometimes called channelizers?
No Description

betterquesting:10.name:8: we are all matter out of place AA
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
It happens in the multiverse. Something goes wrong, and you die. In this particular corner of the multiverse the penalty isn't that bad. So long as you can find your tombstone...

You should see a new beacon visible on the horizon. You can also see the beacon on your JourneyMap (opens with "j" by default). Go there and you should see a tombstone nearby. In most case the tombstone will appear however it may be very difficult to get to. Like if you ended up in a lava ocean, or fell out the bottom of the world.

If you right click the tombstone it will tell you who it belongs to. To retrieve your items, destroy the tombstone. It is quicker with a pickaxe. Note that your items may end up scattered about when you destroy the tombstone. If you died somewhere hazardous (like in a lava ocean) you should ensure there is ample enclosed space to help keep your items safe. You will end up with your tombstone as a memento of what happened.

Try to not become moop again.

* pre-reqs for water seed
* pre-reqs for inferieum seed

Alright, class! Today we're learning how to make leather!

§nTask 1§r: Make the leather.

* essence crafting basics
* essence growth basics
Make some water, grow some water.

There is some content within the Tribes That May Be multiverse which crosses back and forth between realities.

Things such as external tools and services which may be used to extend the Block Rock Desert experience, or resources which the player may (or may not) find valuable.

We aren't going to force these upon you.

If you would like these quests to be accessible then must explicitly consent.

But if you do, there is no going back.

It ain't easy having a good time and one of the ways this manifests is by having to learn. Your trusty guidebook will get you only so far. The Tribes That May Be multiverse is full of guides, manuals, and books. While you can easily make book shelves to keep them on, we often want to keep some of these books close at hand.

Enter the Akashik Tome. You can add (many but not all) books to it by combining them (one at a time) with your Akashik Tome in a crafting grid. Access the stored books by right clicking on empty space with the Akashik Tome in your hand.

You will be presented with a list of books in the tome. Select one and then yor tome will turn into that book. When you are done, left click on empty space with the book selected. To remove a particular book from the tome, select it, and then drop it (default "q" while crouching (default "shift").
Some words about fuel generation and how hard it is I guess

There is no shortage of furniture for storing your things. But some of the furniture is classier than others.

The nightstand is one of those.

You don't have to put it next to your bed, but why wouldn't you?

It's classier that way.

betterquesting:10.name:8: When all you have is a hammer...
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
There are a lot of things you can do with a hammer. In this multiverse zone trip, the Immersive Engineering hammer is used to adjust blocks. You can use it to rotate supported blocks, and configure a variety of Immersive Engineering things such as flood lights and capacitors.

Craft an Immersive Engineering hammer.

betterquesting:10.name:8: To Do or Not To Do
betterquesting:10.desc:8: clipboards are rad tho
Make some vehicles. Will need to put a bunch of words in here about how the mod works.

There are three different sizes of speakers that you can build. Let's start with the smallest. You are going to need some nether quartz and a diamond for this, but don't worry - these can both be found in the Block Rock Desert.

Once you have created your speaker you can attach it to a record player or a radio with speaker wire. To do so, select the speaker wire. You can then right click on the source block (radio or record player) and then right click on the speaker. Note that the speaker wires don't go very far - only about 7 blocks.

You can remove speaker wire by using wire cutters on the speaker or source block.

Why stop with just one hammer? If you want to repair vehicles you find or make, you are going to need at least one more...

Craft a hammer from the MrCrafyfish Vehicles mod.

We are going to need clay. Probably a lot of clay, especially if you want to make your house out of brick. Which you do not need to really do.

Lots of things are made out of clay. Cooking utensils, flower pots, along with crafting equipment.

Find some clay! You can usually find it underground.
There are better records in this modpack. I shold write some words about that later.

Now that you've got a bucket, I've got a trick to teach you.

You can use it to purify even §omore§r water.

But! Now that said pure water is in a bucket, you can fill an external vessel with it to prepare for longer treks across the dusty, dusty wasteland...

§nTask 1§r: Fill your bucket with water.
§nTask 2§r: Purify the water in your bucket by heating it in your furnace.

Tips!
You can not only put your purified water in a storage vessel with your bucket, but also take it out the same way.
This will help you refill your canteen on the go.

Alright, the time for hand holding is just about over.

From now on, the quests are going to get pared down to only the essentials.

Being that it's almost time to leave in search of a suitable home and the fact that you've gotten this far, I'm sure you can manage.

But how are you supposed to get where you're going with all the possessions you've surely gathered by now?

Well, unless you want to practice extreme minimalism and discard everything you own, you're going to need a backpack.

§
§n§n§r§nTask 1§r: Make yourself a backpack.

*The crate you receive as a reward for this quest will keep its contents when picked up, making it perfect for travel.

*Will incorporate some of duplicate quest text;

It takes a lot of supplies and preparation to have a good time. You are going to need more than your pockets and your tool belt. The simple backpack can be upgrade as you gain access to more advanced materials. Always make sure to empty it before you upgrade!

To put it on, bring up your inventory (default key "e"). Click on the baubles icon (a little ring in the upper right of your avatar display). Shift-click the backpack and you will now be wearing it (assuming nothing was already in the back slot).

betterquesting:10.name:8: Every day is hump day when you're a camel. <3

betterquesting:10.desc:8:
If you're feeling like you could use a another pocket or two to put something nifty in, a tool belt could be the answer.

So... uh... make one.

§nTask 1§r: Make a tool belt.

*You can upgrade this as you progress, so don't dismiss it so readily based on its currently limited capacity.

Copied text;
There are a lot of tools and widgets to juggle as we stumble through autonomous zone to autonomous zone. A great way to  hold them is with a toolbelt! As common in the Block Rock Desert as throughout the multiverse. As much a fashion statement as they are practical.

You can craft one with leather, iron, and string. Out of the box, they can hold two items. Using an anvil you cand slap more tool pouches on to your belt and hold up to nine things!

To add something to your toolbelt, have the item you want to place into your toolbelt selected in your hotbar and press "R" (default key). You will then be presented with a selection wheel and if the toolbelt is not full, select insert. To remove something from your toolbelt, have an empty slot on your hotbar selected, and again press "R". Select the item you wish to extract.

You've officially proven yourself ready to venture out into the world and make a home for yourself.

In an effort to facilitate that, I've provided you with some magical fruit.

Once you eat the fruit, you'll be able to fly for a limited time (indicated by a countdown timer at the top-right corner of your view).

Be wise about how you use this boon and don't fly too high, lest you fall to your demise.

*
To enable/disable §3creative flight§r, double-tap the §3§5space bar§r.

Architecturecraft is one of several mods included specifically to allow you to make things prettier. It allows for the shaping of almost any block into columns, window frames, roofing tiles, and other things.

You can use the Finishing Hammer to rotate these modified blocks after they have been placed.

Most hand tools are going to get made in the Smeltery. It's a piece of crafting equipment that is comprised of multiple blocks put together in a particular way.

You are going to need a lot of clay, sand, and gravel.

You didn't bring enough food to last in this endless desert and eating cooked rabbit will get boring quickly.

Time to start the camp kitchen.

Craft some cooking utensils.

As a reward you get either a tool rack for storing your kitchen tools, or a fruit basken to keep fruit in!

Let's start making some fancier tools. Almost every hand tool, or weapon, you will want to use will be created using Tinkers Construct. It involves a few pieces of creafting equipment. You have already made the crafting station. You will probably want to read the manual - Materials and You - to get a better handle on how Tinkers Construct works.

Craft a stencil table and a part builder. You can use these for making custom tools, and you will want them as you get into the smeltery to make fancyier custom tools.

For your reward you can choose between a pattern chest and a part chest. These are purpose built storage items for the little fiddly bits you will end up with as part of a Tinkers workshop.

The Big Book allows you to keep notes or write stories. You can write up to 256 pages and eight different tabbed sections. There is control over the text formatting as well. You can save and edit at any time.

If you ever decide that the book is finished then you can sign it and then mass produce it if you would like. Note that a signed book may not be edited any more, and you cannot undo signing.

The Smeltery is going to be your friend. You will use it to make other friends - tools, weapons, and armore that you can upgrade, repair, and name. Before you go too far down this path make sure to read the manual - Materials and You.

You should have enough material to make a 3x3x2 smeltery with two drains, one tank, a casting table, and a casting basin.

You should construct it somewhere safe.

At this point you have probably discovered that you can jump and you can fall. You can't jump very far, but you can fall quite far, depending on local geography. There are several things you can do to change how this works.

Stairs are pretty handy for going between floors of your house, or down into the mines.

Ladders are quite functional however you do need to be a little agile to use make (if not use) them.

As a reward, you get a step ladder! You can't use it without being a little bit agile though. Under your inventory screen (e by default but we should know that by now) on the left hand side you will find the "skiils" tab. When you click this you have a skill selection screen. You will need to have a 2 in agility to use the step ladder. Note that you scroll up and down the skills screen with the mouse wheel (or track pad).

The step ladder is equally handy for hanging fairy lights as it is reaching the top of trees you are chopping down.

The step ladder is pretty neat but sometimes you need a bit of an extra reach. The rope ladder can be placed on the edge of a cliff, or at the top of a cavern, or along the side of a wall. It will drop down as far as it can (based on how much rope ladder you have in your inventory). You do need to be a bit more agile to use this than the step ladder.

Equally as handy for rescuing people who have fallen down wells as it is for dropping into mystical caverns from the roof.

The step ladder gives you a bit of an extra step, and the rope ladder can help you get into places in a pinch.

Scaffolding is for building things. The basic scaffolding can be built off of itself, but will decay over time. It's pretty cheap to make so you can go all out.

As you progress into the realm of fully automated queer block utopia you will gain access to more permanent scaffolding made out of creosote treated wood and steel.

But for now, you can use the varios scaffoldings provided by the Cyclic mod in order to help you build things.

Well you've found a place that is probably going to be your home for now. Time to start collecting things!

There is an amazing about of flexibility in terms of how you can store stuff but it generally all starts with a simple wooden chest.

Chests can be placed next to each other to double in size in an aesthetically pleasing way. You can make increasingly larger chests (and other things for storage) as you progress.

As a reward, you get an upgrade to expand the size of a single chest.

If you are the kind of logistics fetishist I think you are then some of the first todo items on your clipboard are related to sustainable storing the rapidly escalating amount of blocks you have collected. Storage Drawers are a great way of doing so and they can be expanded and make use of late game tech as well!

The framing table may be used with framed drawers to use any kind of wood for your drawers. You can actually mix and match the different kinds of wood as well to make patterns if you would like

We've talked about the questbook and how helpful it is to your adventure but what other books are there?

You may have noticed that you started out with a Journal. Throughout your time in the multiverse you will find bits and pieces of lore. As you collect these they will end up in your journal and you can read them.

Some lore will be part of the story, some lore will be the stories of others, and some will be informative and help you learn about difference pieces of the Tribes That May Be experience.
It ain't a real party without some blinky lights. You can attach the strobe light, laser, and laser cluster to a source block (such as a radio or record player) using speaker wire.

Once you get locked into a serious vinyl collection the tendency is to take it as far as you can.

The Disc Holder can be used to hold all kinds of records, along with frequency crystals.

It looks a lot classier than a milk crate.

The Tribes That May Be multiverse has a bunch of tracks included from it's various mods. You can collect them all because you are a completionist, or you can make an old school stereo and listen in that way.

To use the stereo, place it in world. Right click to turn it on and cycle between the tracks. Shift right click to turn it off.

The sleeping bag is OK but it's not quite the same as a proper bed. A normal bed will set a home location for you, so you end up going back there when you die. Without a bed, you will end up back in D-Lot when you die, and nobody wants that.

Craft a bed, place it somewhere you want to wake up in. After either a restfull nights sleep, or death. Both are inevitable.

You can also place two beds side by side, if that fits your lifestyle and/or aesthetic.

The only thing better than a good nights sleep is spending the day in a hammock.

To hang a hammock you need two rope & nails. And some hammock cloth. And some trees.

You can place the role and nail into the trees. Make sure there is a straight line between them (along the N/S or E/W axis). Once you've done that, right click with the hammock cloth on one of the nails. The max distance is about five blocks.

Sweet day dreams.

Another way to spend the day or night is in a comfortable couch. You can place multiple couch pieces side by side to make sweet sectionals.

You can make different colors of couch by dying your wool prior to making the couch.
A nice coffee table helps bring the room together. You can place items on the coffee table, like books.

You may have noticed all the dry gardens all over this desert. Chances are you've broken some and gotten some things from them. You can use these things, along with various kitchen implements, to craft real food.

Make some fruit salad and make some garden soup.

Enjoy your fruit salad and savor your garden soup.

To start using the records you have found, you are going to need a record player. The record player has a small speaker built-in but if you are going to throw a serious party then you will want to build some larger speakers.

While it's fun to shuffle around records in a block world, streaming in outside sources can also be nice. The Better Records Radio can be used with tuned frequency crystals to bring mp3 streams into minecraft.

You will need at least three frequency crystals - one for the Frequency Tuner, one for the Radio, and one to tune to a radio station.

To use the frequency tuner, place it in world and right click on it. You can then specify a name and a URL to an icecast2 stream. Once those are in place, put the crystal in the tuning slot and click "Tune". Note that only icecast2 streams are supported.

Once you have a tuned crystal, you can place it in the radio. Shift right click on the radio with an empty hand to open/close. When the radio is open, right click with a tuned frequency crystal to start the music. Right click on the radio open radio with a frequency crystal and an empty hand will cause the crystal to be ejected.

You can use a record inscriber to encode a HTTP url containing a mp3 into a record. I think it also works with ogg files?

Anyway, the default Better Records configuration in the Tribes That May Be modpack supports mp3's up to 800mb (bc some sets go into the sunrise) and should start playing the music as it is downloading.

Your mileage may vary.

You're finally here! It's true.

But where's everyone else?

Well, at least you've got me, your trusty quest book.

In case it isn't obvious, your current priority is survival.

First, try to remember what color your sleeping bag is and §5l-click§r §""§2Claim§r".

Next, exit my interface and take stock of your inventory.

Also, be sure to take a look at the quest "Such A User..." for some helpful info and a free goody.

The human body is generally anywhere from 50-78% water.

You should probably try to stay somewhere in that range if you'd like to survive.

Keep an eye on those little water drops at the bottom of your field of view to make sure you don't turn into a dusty little piece of jerky.

§nTask 1§r: Drink some water from your canteen.

betterquesting:10.name:8: So much for shade in the desert...
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
That is how Minecraft generally starts.

You punch a tree until you get a log of some kind.

Then you make planks out of it with your §obare, hands§r (or the 2x2 grid in your inventory).

Finally, before you know it you're being chased through a darkened desert by coyotes.

For the moment being, let's just stick to getting a crafting station built.

§nTask 1§r: Punch a tree until you get a log.
§n§nTask 2§r: Turn that log into planks.
§nTask 3§r: Make those planks into a crafting table.
§nTask 4§r: Turn that crafting table into a crafting station.

Moving a drawer full of thousands of pieces of cobblestone, or pieces of flesh, or beer, or whatever you keep in your drawers - it sounds terrible.

You should make some packing tape. You can seal up a set of storage drawers by right clicking on it with the tape. You can then safely break the drawers with an axe and move it.

You should probably find a water source and use it to fill your canteen.

You can do this by §9crouch§ring + §9r-click§ring on a water block with your canteen in hand.

If it's an emergency situation, you can drink straight from standing water by doing the same thing with an empty hand, but you probably shouldn't do too much of that...

But fret not, thirsty wanderer, you can purify the water in a canteen with the handy charcoal filters you got.

All you need to do is combine your full canteen and a charcoal filter in a §2crafting grid§r to get some pure, tasty, H20.

§nTask 1§r: Refill your canteen and purify the water inside.

There is a lot of mining and crafting in Minecraft (never would've guessed from the name, right?).

Even in this particular Minecraft multiverse you'll need to do a significant amount of both before we can get to fully-automated, luxury, queer-block socialism.

It will take a bit of work to get there, and as you progress you will need to improve not only your tools, but the skills necessary to use them as well.

§
§n§r§nTask 1§r: Make your first pickaxe!

*As you gain experience, make sure to check the skills tab of your inventory to allocate the experience you'll be getting.

That trusty knife of yours is great and all, but let's be real... you should probably find a way to better defend yourself.

It's about time you armed yourself with §mknowledge!§r some sort of weapon.

To the right, you'll see a few different options for weapons that should be easily craftable with the resources you currently have at your disposal.

You should probably have a helmet too, now that you're thinking of running around swinging a weapon at things that can fight back...

I've got you covered. <3

§nTask 1§r: Craft one of the listed weapons.

Quick Tip;
An axe will not only help defend yourself, but it can also help you get wood faster if you whack some trees with it.

You will eventually fill up your drawers. Fortunately they can be upgraded for more storage, or more features.

Let's start with more storage.

Craft a basic storage upgrade.

Two things;

§nTask 1§r: Mine blocks.
§nTask 2§r: Make a furnace.

§l§r§lQuick Tip:
§rIf you mine down far enough, you'll find "bedrock". Bedrock looks like the icon for this quest. You can't mine bedrock.
Don't let your eyes deceive you while diligently swinging away at it with your pickaxe. It's not going to work. I promise, on my honor as real news.

Being in a new environment can be challenging, as most of us are likely aware.

In an effort to mitigate frustration from UI troubles, listed below are some excerpts from my most helpful, less snarky pages that should serve you well.

Caveat; If I were to attempt to explain every possible interaction available to you, I wouldn't have any room in my pages for the §ofun§r quests, so this should be seen as a relatively brief primer and starter guide.

When in doubt, I recommend checking your controls, tooltips, or the quest you're working on if it requires a specific action.

§1Quest Book§r
First and foremost, while you can access the amazingly helpful knowledge I contain by using my physical form, I can also be accessed via hotkey (§1§d§5~§  §rby§r default), even if you lose me!

Next, while I try to be as succinct as possible and present everything on one page, you may need to §3scroll§r or use the §2arrows§r at the bottom of my pages to see an entry in full.
I apologize. I'm not as thin as I once was, as I'm now thick with knowledge!
Anyway, let's test the functions I mentioned on this entry.

§1Just Enough Items (JEI)
§rLet's move on to what will surely be your next best friend after me, the §5§rJEI interface§r.
This is the interface on the right (by default) when your inventory is open.
Its §2search bar§r allows you find just about anything in this multiverse.
Then, with a simple §5l-§r or §5r-click§r on item in question you can both determine how to craft it and what you can craft with it!

§mDon't say anything, but I love the JEI interface. <3§r
*cough*

Alright, back to everything else.

§1General Controls§r
You can exit almost any interface with §l§5esc§r.

Almost all other controls can be found, edited, and completely made a mess of via the "§l§2Controls§l§r" option in the main menu. Careful.

§WWhile we're on the topic of being careful, you can §3sneak/crouch§r by holding the assigned hotkey (§5shift§r by default) while you move.

§3Sneaking§r can help you avoid detection as well as prevent you from walking off the edge of the block you're on. Just be careful not to get hit by something, as it can easily push you over the edge to your demise.

Now, let's talk about how to §3sprint§r! You can do so by holding down the assigned hotkey (§5ctrl§r by default) while you move.

Just bear in mind that if you're too hungry or thirsty, §3sprinting§r won't be an option.

Wait! What good is all this sneaking and sprinting knowledge if you don't know how to move around in the first place?!
Your movements are mapped to §5w§r, §5a§r, §5s§r, §5d§r by default, essentially creating a left-handed set of arrow keys.

Aaand finally, certain items and machines have alternate functions when §5l-§r or §5r-clicking§r while holding §5shift§r or §5ctrl§r regardless of whether you're moving or not.

For example, you can §3equip§r and §3unequip§r items and gear by §5shift§r + §3§5l-clicking§r on them in your inventory. 

Now that you're likely feeling a little lost, let's talk about getting found.

§1Journey Map§r
You've got a map!
Yeah, you've got a minimap at the top right (default), but you can look at a larger version via hotkey (§1§5j§r by default).
Through this§r interface you can set and remove waypoints, see other nearby (or not-so-nearby players), and view details of the areas you've discovered.

This probably all seems like a lot, but I promise you'll get the hang of it as you fiddle around and explore this bizarre, cuboid reality.
Just remember, it's all about having a good time§m and avoiding unintended injuries, fatal mishaps, and unexpected creeper explosions§r.

This is it, your last tip! I'll try to simplify your quests by clearly labeling what you need to do to finish it at the bottom of each entry.
See below;

§nTask 1§r: Check the first box.
§nTask 2§r: Check the second box.

Over the course of your adventures, you're bound to come across many not-so-friendly entities.

It's truly a kill or be killed environment out here.

Time to show your mettle and reap the rewards.

§nTask 1§r: Kill a husk.
§nTask 2§r: Collect some rotten flesh.

*While the first task is to kill a husk, both husks and zombies, as well as a couple other unfriendlies, drop rotten flesh.

Congratulations! Your furnace is your first piece of significant "technology"!

There are a few different things you can do with a your fancy, new fire box. Let's try a couple now.

§nTask 1§r: Make some charcoal.
§nTask 2§r: Cook some food.

*
There are many things that can fuel your furnace, some of which you may not want to put in there (tools, valuable items, etc.).
Different things have different burn rates, which you can see by holding §5shift§r while hovering over the thing in question with your cursor.

By now, you should have an almost full set of leather armor.

While it's not the best defensive equipment you can get, it's better than nothing.

§nTask 1§r: Make some leather pants.

Bonus Task; Try to get that juicy peach into those tight new leather pants. ;D
^^ Not a real task. Don't overthink it.

Tables can be used to keep all kinds of things on it. They can also be used for the pure aesthetic of having tables. There are a variety of tables which can be made in this shard of the multiverse, so pick the one you like, and put something on it. Many tables can be placed next to each other to create larger tables. In case you have friends over, and they want to place things on the table.

People tend to have tables in places where they hang out.

Everything may be terrible but at least you can grill up some decent eats.

You can cook a variety of meats on this grill. Great for entertaining.

betterquesting:10.name:8: The revolution will not be televised
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
You can use this TV to display looped animated GIFs.

To set the GIFs, right click it with an empty hand. You can also turn it on and off from this display.

You can right click with the remote in the direction of the TV to change the channel. Shift right click to turn it off/on.

Sometimes walls are too much. Sometimes you just need a little visual barrier between parts of your home.

The paper wall can be used for this. Lightweight, easy to make with what can be found in the Block Rock Desert, and (most importantly) classy as all get out.
Flower pots are nice. You can put flowers in them and add a splash of color to your home, or your container.

You can put things you would like to show off in the item frame.  You can dye the frame if you would like.

You can place an item in the frame by holding the item in your hand and right clicking on the placed frame. You can then rotate the item by right clicking it. If you would like to get the item back then punch it.

Punching an empty frame will knock if off the wall. If you find yourself doing this often you may wish to speak to a therapist.

The reward for this quest is a painting. Upon placing it on the wall you get to choose the art.

Rugs can really tie the room together. Carpets are a decent simulacrum in this simulacrum of spectacles.

You can create carpet out of any color of wool. Once you get the right chisel, you can create patterened carpet too.

The reward is a door mat. Place it outside of your home. Upon doing so you will be prompted to write a welcome message.

betterquesting:10.name:8: All the pretty flags, all the pretty lights
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
The fairy lights mod gives you a bunch of pretty things you can make. Craft individual penant flags, bunting, tinsel, or lights. You can then combine them into a string.  You can even mix and match different colors of the same type.


You can then string them together using two iron ingots and a piece of string. The iron ingots go in the upper right and left of a crafting table. The string goes in the middle. Place up to six bits (lights, penant flags, etc) in the lower six slots. This will give you a single string of flags/lights/whatever that can stretch for up to 32 blocks.

To place the strings, right click on a block (most work for this purpose). You can then right click on a second block to complete the placement. 

You can turn the lights on/off by right clicking on them with an empty hand.

You can tighten the slack of the string by right clicking them with a stick. You can increase the slack by right clicking with a piece of string.

Some words about fully automated luxury queer block utopias.

* mystical agriculture
* mass production
* etc
It is a little dusty in here.
Vehicles are real, and pretty cool.
